2026-04-21 01:31:00 | INFO     | DiagnosticAssistantLLM | OUTPUT: suggestion_type='hypothesis' action_type=None action_target=None action_description=None suspected_components=['Control Module 3 input/output cabling between modules 2 and 3'] hypothesis_explanation='Measurements show that at the output of Control Module 2 there is a correct 12 V / 0 V pair. When Control Module 3 is disconnected, all its internal conductors (input + to output +, input − to output −) have good continuity (~0.1 Ω), so the module itself is not internally open or shorted. However, when Module 3 is reconnected in the chain with all switches ON, only the incoming 12 V conductor at the input side of Module 3 is at 11.96 V; the indicator LED branch, the output conductors, and even the nominal input 0 V are all at ~0 V and no voltage appears across the LED+resistor branch. This is only consistent with the cables between Module 2 and Module 3 being mis-mated/swapped—i.e., the 12 V and 0 V lines from Module 2 are not plugged into the intended 12 V and 0 V input ports of Module 3 (for example, 12 V from Module 2 may be going into Module 3’s indicator branch or negative terminal, or both input connectors may be cross-connected). Because all four conductors inside Module 3 are intact, the fault must be in the configuration/connection between the two modules rather than an internal component failure. Correcting the mating of the two connectors so that Control Output Cable (+) 2 goes to Control Input Cable (+) 3 and Control Output Cable (−) 2 goes to Control Input Cable (−) 3 should restore normal operation and allow downstream LEDs and the load to function when all switches are ON.'
